op align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=x@nuclearspace>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 180<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/5/02 6:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> I believe the biggest problem that we will have for near-light speed travel will be intersteller debris.  The Earth is surrounded by fragments of ice called the Oort Cloud that extends over a light-year out.  Using railguns, NASA has shown what happens to material struch at hypervelocities (1-10 km/s).  Imagine what would happen if you hit something at 10% the speed of light or 18,600 miles/s (30,000 km/s).  I believe the impact will would create a hole extending the length of the ship.  This will reek havoc on those on board.  This may be the reason why Earth has not been visited by aliens in its 5 billion year history or why, as Frank Tipler believes, we don't see Von Neumann probes or alien colonies in every star system in the Milky Way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 337<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/6/02 2:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> I think there's no denying that jumping to lightspeed in a solar system would be paramount to suicide.  Even interstellar space is likely filled with enough debris here and there that you could hardly make a straight shot safely even if you had a method for repelling dust particles out of the way.  I've read theories that postulated various ways of neutralizing the threat of dust in a ship travelling close to lightspeed.  I'll dig out some of my books and post them.   I think the biggest barrier to relativistic travel though is the energy requirements, particularly when your up there in the 90%+ range.  No windmills will generate the energy required to produce the anti-matter or lasers required for such speeds, that's for sure. Maybe alien civilizations have a tendency to shun technology which allows them to generate ungodly amounts of power.  Are we the only planet with anti-nuclear activists?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1365<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/6/02 9:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> As far as the discovery of an alien civilization goes, I think it could be more of a matter of time.  Consider that we have had the ability to transmit radio signals for about 100 years out of our entire history.  Who is to say that alien civilizations haven't sprung up and disappeared several times in the past?  Maybe an alien race developed a technologically advanced society 100,000 earth years ago, then died out 50,000 years ago... and lived on a planet that was less than 50,000 light years away?  We would never know they existed because any radio signals they may have generated would have petered out before we developed the technology to detect them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 70<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/8/02 1:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  impacts</span><hr size=1> Interstellar space is so empty that We need not worry about debris impacts very much. Releasing some dust<br>
from a starship in its path would destroy any debris that might exist there.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 352<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/8/02 6:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> Even though I used to subscribe to the rare Earth theory, I'm questioning whether it's really all that unlikely that other intelligent life exists out there.  It wasn't very long ago when you could find numerous scientists who though that it was rare for stars to have planets and we know how that turned out.  And yeah, we've only had the ability to communicate via radio for only about a 100 years which is absolutely infinitesmal in cosmic time.  It seems that civilizations tend to develop very rapidly technology wise once they reach a certain point.  We went from riding around in horsedrawn buggies to flying to the moon in the span of a generation so perhaps a lot of civilizations destroy themselves with nuclear weapons or whatever before they even have a chance to exist for very long in a technically advanced state.  We might be an exception to the rule if we manage to live much longer. <br>
