theory for civilization. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 359<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/9/02 6:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> I think in a lot of ways the yo-yo aspect is starting to manifest itself in our own civilization even without having to use weapons of mass destruction. With the misanthropic and luddite attitudes that seem to be gripping the planet it wouldn't surprise me if society comes to a halt energy and technology wise and then begins a slow creep backwards into a new darkage of sorts.  With our modern day inquisition, the guardians of political correctness, free thought and expression could become a rare commodity.  I think poisonous ideas can destroy a society just as effectively as nuclear warheads.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2398<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 6:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> I don't think interstellar debris will be much of a problem by the time we actually have interstellar vehicles. Propulsion technology can be used in reverse to clear a path ahead. It counters the drive but wouldn't be nearly as powerful. Radar could detect dangerous particles ahead of time so that a more intense laser or plasma wave could knock it aside. Interstellar craft are going to be huge. Project Star Wars was essentially Orion technology in reverse. A concept still being researched. Just as much of the work descended from Orion is still being followed up for weapons applications. <br>
If we could only get one Orion up we might be able to build a massive reflector dish and spy on neighbouring star systems. I doubt anybody nearby has reached our level but we might get some glimpses of Alien Forest. That would be enough to get the whole world behind space technology development. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1418<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 11:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> Interesting:<br>
<br>
We build a massive telescope and detect a primitive civilization.<br>
Something on the technological equivalant of pre-industrial<br>
revolution.  Lets place the discovered civilization at 25 light years<br>
distance.<br>
<br>
After the discovery it was decided to build a super orion that <br>
could attain 10 percent the speed of light.  Recent medical discoveries<br>
have developed a form of suspended animation that would allow a crew to <br>
make the voyage there and back while only aging a few years.<br>
<br>
OK.  25 year old telescope image<br>
plus let's assume a 25 year construction period for the super orion<br>
plus trip time one way of 250 years (at least)<br>
<br>
For a total from discovery to 'first contact' of 300 years.<br>
<br>
If the alien civilization developed technology as rapidly as we<br>
did, then it's possible that by the time the first expedition arrived,<br>
the alien society could be more advanced then the arriving earthlings!<br>
<br>
Or, the Orion crew arrives only to discover that several expeditions had <br>
passed them up with more advanced starships in the 250+ years it takes for their voyage. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 152<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 12:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> That scenario, while possible, is highly unlikely. What are the odds that we would discover a civ. that is only 300 years away from interstellar spaceflight? It would be far more likely, me thinks, that this civ. is still in the stone age, or far more advanced than we. And since SETI has detected anything of note, yet, it probably is safe to assume that any other intelligence within 30 light years is in the stone age, or closer to it than we are.<br>
<br>
However, the super Orion being overtaken by a more advanced ships seems almost probable. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 367<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 3:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> With the new breed of interferometric space-based telescopes on the boards it might not be long before we have some idea of which extra-solar planets might harbor life.  Even though these telescopes won't be able to image the surfaces directly they can still blot out the light of the parent star and gather information on the light being reflected from the planets.  If the spectrum shows a high level of free oxygen on the planet it's almost a dead give away that there is likely somekind of life present since oxygen needs to be replenished on a fairly constant basis.  If we do develop the ability to image these planets directly for things like forests and do indeed find some I agree that it could lead to a revolution in thinking toward spaceflight.  On the other hand though I think that planets that are abundant in life should be left alone even though it would be hard not to give into the temptation to go somewhere new and start over fresh away from the political influences on Earth.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 264<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/11/02 3:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Forget about interstellar rockets.</span><hr size=1> It's silly to think of using any kind of system to travel between stars which depends on burning a fuel to push more fuel which is later burned to push still more fuel which burns to push even more fuel.<br>
 Even if the fuel is antimatter.<br>
 It's like suggesting to a 13th century explorer that in the future, we'll fly between continents in hours. He'll speculate on a 250 ton flying ship, which has stupendous masts and sails to catch enough wind to push itself at mach .8<br>
 How do you have enough rowers to move at 560 mph?<br>
<br>
<br>
Tim1965<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt;  Interstellar space is so empty that We need not worry<br>
about debris impacts very much. Releasing some dust from<br>
a starship in its path would destroy any debris that might<br>
exist there.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Very good plan. A few tons of a gas would do; give it a push ahead of the path of the ship itself. Designing the ship with something like a whipple shield (multi-layered shield in front of the ship's path) solves the rest.<br>
<br>
 Though really, it's not that much of a problem. Any ship should have some kind of detection, so that anything big enough to get past the gas-cloud and still ruin the ship (asteroids) can be detected, and the ship given some delta-V to maneuver away from the collision path.<br>
At very high fractions of C, forget about it. Anything in your path won't be seen: your radar beams and EM shields are restricted to photonic speeds, barely faster than the ship itself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; having something like an electrical field at the front of<br>
the ship that could repel dust particles might solve the<br>
problem. I think the electrical field would have to operate<br>
constantly and cover every square nanometer of vulnerable<br>
area on the ship...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Still haven't seen any good evidence that such a thing is possible. The space colony studies showed that, unless you can promise some radically new theoretical &amp; applied science breakthrough, simple mass shielding (whether dumb rock for radiation or layered chobham armor) is the smplest and surest.<br>
 You need laser to ionise neutral particles, so they and the similarly charged particles are pushed away by the fields. You then need some way to deal with the oppositely charged stuff which is immensely attracted to your charged ship. You need equally huge amounts of power to neutralise the charge on the ship so that things which get past (and some things will) aren't wildly attracted to the ship.<br>
 For each of these shield levels, you need several times more power than the ship needs to push itself to a speed which is high enough to require such shielding.<br>
<br>
<br>
 I've written before about Savage's interstellar mass-driver transportation scheme. This addresses the interstellar gas impacts and the power issues.<br>
 Forget about doing it in any near-term (the next few centuries) timescale. As said before, the crew will be passed en-route by later travelers, who go faster, for less cost.<br>
 Not an oil-burning, Space Shuttle (flying camel) using bunch of savages, but an emerging Kardashev-2 civilization.<br>
 Picture a cloud of habitats, factories, and various other solar collectors extending from the orbit of Mercury to out past Neptune.<br>
 From outside, the Sun seems embedded in a cloud of orbiting stuff (the Dyson Cloud).<br>
 Next, huge 10AU diameter hemispheric caps are placed over the north &amp; south polar regions of the solar system, to collect the sunlight which otherwise would escape there (since it's difficult to have habitats in polar orbits to complete the coverage). If they're light enough, sunlight pressure keeps them aloft against the Sun's gravity. Magnetic sail technology serves for station-keeping.<br>
<br>
 That's the power source for interstellar travel: a million-mile diameter free stellar fusion furnace. (Definition of a K-2 civilization is one which uses all the available energy of their star).<br>
<br>
 A few hundred smallish asteroids are taken apart to make EM accelerator coils, each a few hundred km diameter. These use magsails to maneuver into positions so a ship can be thrown from one to the next, from the inner solar system to the last coils out in the Oort cloud (By this time, fully settled and mapped so there are no surprising chunks of stuff -which are more resources to be mined for space colonies).<br>
 Using the energy from the Sun, ships are tossed up to a high fraction of C. (Sure, it's wasteful and it'll never be cheap, but it's workable for them in the future.)<br>
 A few months acceleration, a few weeks coasting between stars, then a few more months deceleration at the destination colony star (which recovers much of the energy used to send the ship on its way.)<br>
<br>
 At anything above .95C, ships must be streamlined against the interstellar gasses, and aerodynamic flaps &amp; spoilers may work for turning...<br>
 The ship's leading edges will glow from the friction of interstellar H2 atoms, and there'll be a plainly optically visible and RF audible wake as the ship screams past an observer.<br>
Relativistic time dilation cuts the inhabitant's trip down to a few weeks subjective time, though it's still 20+ years to go 20 light-years, to an outside observer.<br>
<br>
 For this K-2 culture, interstellar mapping expeditions are robotic probes, pushed from the home system. Thrown to a fast cruise by power beams or massdrivers, the ships use magsails to slow down &amp; explore the target system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 374<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/11/02 6:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=503.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Intersteller debris and relativistic impacts</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Next, huge 10AU diameter hemispheric caps are placed over the north &amp; south polar regions of the solar system, to collect the sunlight which otherwise would escape there (since it's difficult to have habitats in polar orbits to complete the coverage). If they're light enough, sunlight pressure keeps them aloft against the Sun's gravity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
